 Janeiro, the meanings of the principal institutions of the constitutional monarchy established in 1822-24 (which were celebrated on days of national festivity), and the challenges to the imperial regime that took place during the festivities. While officialdom and the narrow elite sought to control civic rituals, the urban lower classes took an active part in them, although their popular festivities were not always welcomed by the elite. Days of National Festivity is the first book to provide a systematic analysis of civic ritual in a Latin American country over a long period of time-and in doing so, it offers new perspectives on the Brazilian empire, elite and popular politics, and urban culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aFestivalsxPolitical aspectsxHistoryx19th centuryxBrazilxRio de Janeiro. 0aFestivalsxPolitical aspectszBrazilzRio de JaneiroxHistoryy19th century. 0aHolidaysxHistoryx19th centuryxBrazil. 0aHolidayszBrazilxHistoryy19th century. 0aPolitical customs and ritesxHistoryx19th centuryxBrazilxRio de Janeiro. 0aPolitical customs and riteszBrazilzRio de JaneiroxHistoryy19th century. 4aBrazil. 4aBrazilian empire. 4aRio de Janeiro. 4acivic rituals. 4amonarchy. 4amonuments. 4anational holidays. 4apolitical participation. 4apopular festivals. 4atheater. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804786102zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804786102423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804786102.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles